**6. Architectural Implications**

**6.1 Service Layer in the Four-Layer Architecture**

The application management services do not constitute a new
architectural layer. Instead, they are **cross-cutting capabilities that
span all four existing layers**:

**Layer 1 (Data Connector):** Data quality engine, legacy adapter,
external integrations, backup/recovery

**Layer 2 (Business Intelligence):** Rules engine, process orchestrator,
knowledge base, compliance monitoring, calculation verification

**Layer 3 (Relevance Engine):** Work queue prioritization, predictive
routing, proficiency tracking, predicted-need intelligence

**Layer 4 (Dynamic Workspace):** Guided/Expert mode composition,
notification delivery, document requirements UI, case notes, call
logging

**Cross-cutting:** Audit trail (every layer logs),
authentication/authorization (every request validated), health
monitoring (every service reports)

**6.2 Integration Architecture Pattern**

For HYBRID and BUY services, NoUI defines a consistent integration
pattern:

**Adapter Interface:** Each external service is accessed through a
NoUI-defined adapter interface. The adapter abstracts the third-party
API so the core platform never has a direct dependency on a specific
vendor.

**Event-Driven Coupling:** NoUI publishes domain events (case created,
stage advanced, document received). External services subscribe to
relevant events. This loose coupling means swapping an email provider
requires only a new adapter, not platform changes.

**PII Firewall:** No adapter may transmit Restricted or Confidential
data to a cloud service. Adapters running within the Data Connector
boundary may access PII; cloud-side adapters receive only anonymized or
tokenized references.

